HgI$_{2}$ can be found in a variety of forms (Gumi\'{n}ski, 1997): \begin{itemize} \item The ground state, \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_tP6_137_a_d-001}{coccinite} (this structure), also known as red or $\alpha$-HgI$_{2}$ and given the {\em Strukturbericht} designation $C13$.  It is stable up to 135$^\circ$C. \item At higher temperatures this transforms into yellow or $\beta$-HgI$_{2}$ in the \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B_oC12_36_2a_a-001}{HgBr$_{2}$ ($C24$) structure}.  This is stable up to the melting point at 258$^\circ$C. \item (Schwarzenbach, 1969) studied the metastable \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_tI48_141_h_2eg-001}{orange HgI$_{2}$} body-centered tetragonal ($I4_{1}/amd$ \#141) phase. This structure was refined by (Hostettler, 2002). \item (Hostettler, 2002) also found a \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_tP24_137_g_cdf-001}{second orange HgI$_{2}$ phase} in a simple tetragonal ($P4_{2}/nmc$ \#137) cell. \item The last two structures differ by stacking order. (Hostettler, 2002) used them to produce an \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_tP12_115_j_egi-001}{averaged   orange HgI$_{2}$ structure}, space group $P\overline{4}m2$ \#115. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 We use the data for coccinite taken by (Schwarzenbach, 2007) at 293 K. 
 The CIF and POSCAR files contain the data at room temperature, 293 K. \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B_tP6_137_d_a-001}{ZrO$_{2}$ (A2B\_tP6\_137\_d\_a)} and \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_tP6_137_a_d-001}{HgI$_{2}$ (AB2\_tP6\_137\_a\_d)} have similar AFLOW prototype labels (i.e., same symmetry and set of Wyckoff positions with different stoichiometry labels due to alphabetic ordering of atomic species). They are generated by the same symmetry operations with different sets of parameters ({\tt --params}) specified in their corresponding CIF files
